description.text:
I am not sorry about the name.

Anyway, this began with two L-shaped brackets meant to hold up a small iPhone 5c on a desk. Normally, they hold the phone comfortably in landscape mode, but can be pushed together for portrait with minimal impact on the stability. Later on, I decided to make a "floor runner" to hold the brackets at different fixed distances for a variety of holding patterns. At the widest, they hold the 5c comfortably in landscape mode, not sliding or tipping over when navigating apps. With one placed a little closer to the other, the lens is no longer covered up and you've got a small tabletop tripod for unboxing videos or macro photos of your builds. Placing them next to each other holds the phone in portrait mode with access to the home button.

Note: an iPad mini 3 was placed in the holders in landscape mode, and while it held up well enough, it was not stable enough for app navigation, and portrait mode was out of the question. Best to stick with iPhones or most smartphones with screens under 6". Similarly, a Sony Xperia Z Ultra worked perfectly well in landscape mode (with app navigation), but not so much in portrait mode.

Using the smooth rod to locate the bearing block where it has to be, I then used acetone (the parts are printed in an ABS) to weld the side arms in place. Print the item. (designed for platform-free makerboting)
Mirror item and print again. (for opposite side) Use a razor to cut away the outside edges. CAREFUL!!
(sorry this Was printed on an ABP) Depending on how they print, you may want to take a drill and smooth out the Z-Axis holes. They work much better if they are clean and smooth. Do not drill out any wider. Find a bit that fits as is.
Attach the 2 new Z-Axis prints via your 3 surrounding platform screws.
*Do this evenly, do not tighten them down all at once. Do both sides at the same time. Once everything is in place and in line (with z rods inserted), finally tighten them down. The platform should now fall from very top to bottom, effortlessly. If they do not, there is something wrong. Do it again. IMPORTANT
The top Z-Axis stopper-bolts MUST be short (12mm) for clearance.
The Y-Axis also needs a small mod for clearance. To do this, simply take a small scrap wood piece of your makerbot and glue it to the back of your Y-Axis platform where the endstop meets the platform (see last pic). There is no loss of platform build size with doing this. This mod may decrease your Z-Axis build size just slightly. Also, do not attempt to install one at a time, do them both, as the endstop relies on the top piece to stop the platform from crashing into the top. As mentioned, this IS Automated Build Patform compatible. Just be sure to follow my directions and check clearances manually! UPDATE. Second file (delta) fixes a minor clearance issue with the Z axis endstop. Found it was clicking the clip on the way up. Delta file renderes correctly. comments.text: Can you make something to press the bearings in?
comments.author: skitcher

comments.text:
Slightly more tricky, as it is dependent on the thickness of the object you want to push the bearing into, and how deep you want to push it.
On a spinner that is made to be the same height as the bearing, just 2 disks 25mm diameter with an 8mm hole drilled through them both, and an M8 nut and bolt long enough to go through one disk, the spinner, the bearing, and the other disk, then put the nut on the end and tighten it all together.
The disks are wider than the bearings to make sure that the inner hub of the bearing is not pulled out - you could always use steel repair washers.
Or you could use a vise to press the bearings in as mentioned in one of the other comments.

The Removal Press and the Spinner shown were printed using PETG, which I usually run at 245 degrees C. It's a bit stringy, but it cleans up OK, a bit like removing cotton candy or spiderwebs.
Its quite a bit tougher than PLA or ABS, but not as tough as Nylon, or as flexible.
On the roll it's transparent, but printing changes it down to being translucent. The same goes for the clear PETG filament.

You could also use this as a starting point for teaching equivalent fractions.
I have printed a few test pieces and found that with the original files was a bit tricky to read the fractions, so I've increased the font size on the disks for those of us with poorer eyesight.

description.text:
I was heading to San Jose del Cabo for a vacation and watched so many great videos of people all over the world surf fishing for GTs, Roosterfish, Snapper, Bonitos, Mackerel and so much more. Loving fishing, I thought hey let's make some lures!

This represents a mash-up of the features of many of the popular popper designs available from tackle manufacturers from all over. I've printed many of these and they work great, even for big fish they hold up reasonably well given their hollow nature.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator 2X

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

50% or less (50% gives you a 2oz plug)

Notes:

I print them at 50% infill with the popper mouth face down on the table (the whole plug is then vertical) and it prints very well. You are left with very smooth surfaces on the plug ready for paint. I use Fusion spray paint for plastics and hit it with a black back and a red popper face, sometimes a touch of silver on the bottom side.

A 1/2 ounce bell sinker is added to the back of the plug to give it tail weight and then a 0.040 stainless wire is fed through the centreline of the plug to tie it all together. It requires a bit of practice to create the tail loop out of the stainless wire, but look up on YouTube for tutorial videos for that.
